'''Make it brief, Sklifosovskiy''' ({{lang-ru|Короче, Склифосовский!}}) is a popular Russian phrase used to cut short someone's long speech.
==Origins==
The phrase has very little to do with the work of famous Russian physician [[Nikolay Sklifosovskiy|Sklifosovskiy]]. Actually, it originates from the movie ''Kidnapping Caucasian Style, or Shurik's New Adventures'' ("Кавказская пленница, или Новые приключения Шурика", 1966) [http://imdb.com/title/tt0060584/]. Balbes, a negative character of the movie played by [[Yuri Nikulin]], exclaimed: "Make it brief, Sklifosovskiy!" to Shurik and his friend, the positive characters, who, having disguised themselves as vaccination nurses, commenced a long lecture about the benefits of immunization. 

Russians using this phrase are often unaware that it comes from the famous movie. 

